Note: ===================================================================
Note: HIR TO MATLAB GENERATOR
Note: ===================================================================
Note: Translates HIR (High-level Intermediate Representation) into
Note: MATLAB source code for the Translation universal translation system.

Note: This module handles:
Note: - HIR module to MATLAB script/function file generation
Note: - HIR types to MATLAB classdef generation
Note: - HIR functions to MATLAB functions with multiple return values
Note: - HIR operations to MATLAB expressions (matrix vs element-wise)
Note: - HIR control flow to MATLAB statements
Note: - MATLAB-specific feature reconstruction (parfor, spmd, function handles)
Note: - Type mapping (HIR → MATLAB types)

Note: Part of the Translation Translation System
Note: Location: compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/matlab/hir_to_matlab.runa
Note: ===================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_nodes.runa" as HIR
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as ListCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as DictCore

Note: ===================================================================
Note: GENERATION CONTEXT
Note: ===================================================================
Note: Maintains state during HIR→MATLAB generation including type mappings,
Note: indentation tracking, and generated code buffers.

@Reasoning:
The context carries every piece of state the MATLAB emitter must thread
between calls: the HIR-to-MATLAB type-name dictionary, the active indent
level and indent string (MATLAB's de-facto 4-space convention), the line
buffer that accumulates the script, the surrounding class/function nodes
for context-sensitive emission (e.g. method vs free function), and the
matrix-context table that records which expressions need element-wise vs
matrix-mode operators. The context is mutated in place across the entire
emission, so identity not copying is what threads it through recursion.
@End Reasoning
Type called "MatlabGenerationContext":
    Note: Type mapping table (HIR types → MATLAB types)
    type_map as Integer

    Note: Current indentation level
    indent_level as Integer

    Note: Indentation string (typically 4 spaces for MATLAB)
    indent_string as Integer

    Note: Generated code buffer
    code_buffer as Integer

    Note: Current class context (0 if not in a class)
    current_class as Integer

    Note: Current function context (0 if not in a function)
    current_function as Integer

    Note: Matrix operation context (element-wise vs matrix)
    matrix_context as Integer
End Type

Note: ===================================================================
Note: CONTEXT MANAGEMENT
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
The factory installs MATLAB's idiomatic 4-space indent and zero-initialises
the class/function context fields so the first generate_module call cannot
inherit stale references from a previous compilation. The type map and
matrix-context map are constructed eagerly (rather than lazily) so the
emission loop never has to test for null dictionaries on the hot path.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_generation_context" returns Integer:
    Let ctx be a value of type MatlabGenerationContext with
        type_map as proc dict_create from DictCore,
        indent_level as 0,
        indent_string as "    ",
        code_buffer as proc list_create from ListCore,
        current_class as 0,
        current_function as 0,
        matrix_context as proc dict_create from DictCore

    Note: Initialize standard type mappings (HIR → MATLAB)
    proc register_standard_type_mappings from ctx

    Return ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
MATLAB has no static types, but the emitter still emits documentation
comments that mention the source HIR type. Mapping integers and floats to
"double" reflects MATLAB's numeric defaults (every literal is a double
unless cast), while strings become "char" because pre-2017 MATLAB used
char arrays and the string class is still optional. Collections map to
"array" and "struct" because that is how MATLAB represents lists and
dictionaries respectively.
@End Reasoning
Process called "register_standard_type_mappings" takes ctx as MatlabGenerationContext:
    Note: Map HIR primitive types to MATLAB types
    proc dict_set from DictCore with ctx.type_map, proc int_to_string from StringCore with HIR.HIR_TYPE_INTEGER, "double"
    proc dict_set from DictCore with ctx.type_map, proc int_to_string from StringCore with HIR.HIR_TYPE_FLOAT, "double"
    proc dict_set from DictCore with ctx.type_map, proc int_to_string from StringCore with HIR.HIR_TYPE_STRING, "char"
    proc dict_set from DictCore with ctx.type_map, proc int_to_string from StringCore with HIR.HIR_TYPE_BOOLEAN, "logical"

    Note: MATLAB doesn't have explicit type annotations, these are for comments/documentation
    proc dict_set from DictCore with ctx.type_map, proc int_to_string from StringCore with HIR.HIR_TYPE_ANY, "any"
    proc dict_set from DictCore with ctx.type_map, proc int_to_string from StringCore with HIR.HIR_TYPE_VOID, "void"

    Note: Map HIR collection types
    proc dict_set from DictCore with ctx.type_map, proc int_to_string from StringCore with HIR.HIR_TYPE_ARRAY, "array"
    proc dict_set from DictCore with ctx.type_map, proc int_to_string from StringCore with HIR.HIR_TYPE_DICTIONARY, "struct"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Indentation is tracked as a simple integer counter rather than maintaining
a pre-computed string because the emitter occasionally walks back through
the same depth multiple times. The actual whitespace is materialised in
get_current_indent only when a line is emitted.
@End Reasoning
Process called "increase_indent" takes ctx as Integer:
    Set ctx.indent_level to ctx.indent_level plus 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Symmetric counterpart to increase_indent; every emission of a block-closing
'end' must be preceded by a decrease so that the closing keyword aligns
with the opening one. The emitter never decreases past zero because every
increase has a matching decrease in the same generation routine.
@End Reasoning
Process called "decrease_indent" takes ctx as Integer:
    Set ctx.indent_level to ctx.indent_level minus 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Constructing the indentation as a fresh string per line is the canonical
v0.0.8.5 approach: the indent string is small (typically 4 chars) and the
arena allocator amortises the cost. Caching a single indent string per
level was considered but rejected because the buffer would have to be
invalidated whenever the indent string itself was changed by tooling.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_current_indent" takes ctx as Integer returns Integer:
    Let indent be ""
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than ctx.indent_level:
        Set indent to proc string_concat from StringCore with indent, ctx.indent_string
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return indent
End Process

@Reasoning:
emit_line is the single point through which all MATLAB lines reach the
buffer; centralising indentation here guarantees no Process can forget to
prefix the whitespace. The line content is the caller's responsibility -
the emitter never inspects it, which is what allows emit_line to handle
classdef, function, keywords, and expression statements identically.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_line" takes ctx as Integer, line as Integer:
    Let indent be proc get_current_indent from ctx
    Let full_line be proc string_concat from StringCore with indent, line
    proc list_append from ListCore with ctx.code_buffer, full_line
End Process

@Reasoning:
Blank lines bypass the indentation pipeline because MATLAB style guides
require blank lines to be truly empty rather than indented whitespace.
Appending the empty string directly avoids paying for the indent allocation
that emit_line would otherwise produce.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_blank_line" takes ctx as Integer:
    proc list_append from ListCore with ctx.code_buffer, ""
End Process

@Reasoning:
Joining is done with explicit newline separators rather than appending a
trailing newline to every line because MATLAB script files do not require
a trailing newline and adding one would alter the byte-identity of the
output during golden-file regression tests. The single-pass left-fold is
O(N^2) in string length theoretically but in practice the buffer growth
is dominated by the underlying allocator's geometric expansion.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_generated_code" takes ctx as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Join all code lines with newlines
    Let result be ""
    Let count be proc list_length from ListCore with ctx.code_buffer
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than count:
        Let line be proc list_get from ListCore with ctx.code_buffer, i
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, line

        Note: Add newline except for last line
        If i is less than count minus 1:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, "\n"
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: MAIN GENERATION ENTRY POINT
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
The top-level entry point owns the context lifecycle: it creates a fresh
generation context per invocation so concurrent translations of multiple
HIR modules never share mutable state. The two-step (generate, then
collect) pattern lets the caller treat the result as a pure string while
all stateful emission happens against the local ctx.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_matlab_from_hir" takes hir_module as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ctx be proc create_generation_context

    Note: Generate the MATLAB program from HIR module
    proc generate_module with ctx, hir_module

    Note: Get the final generated code
    Let matlab_code be proc get_generated_code from ctx
    Return matlab_code
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: MODULE GENERATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
MATLAB has no notion of modules, packages, or imports: each file declares
either a top-level script or exactly one class/function. The emitter
preserves the module name as a comment for round-tripping back through
universal translation; the body iterates declarations and dispatches
between classdef and function emission, ignoring HIR node kinds that have
no MATLAB representation (e.g. enums - those would be lowered earlier).
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_module" takes ctx as Integer, hir_module as Integer:
    Note: MATLAB doesn't have module-level imports/exports like modern languages
    Note: Generate file-level comments for documentation
    Let module_name be proc hir_get_module_name from HIR with hir_module
    Let has_name be proc string_length from StringCore with module_name
    If has_name is greater than 0:
        Let comment_line be proc string_concat from StringCore with "% Module: ", module_name
        proc emit_line with ctx, comment_line
        proc emit_blank_line from ctx
    End If

    Note: Generate declarations
    Let declarations be proc hir_get_declarations from HIR with hir_module
    Let decl_count be proc list_length from ListCore with declarations
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than decl_count:
        Let decl be proc list_get from ListCore with declarations, i
        Let decl_type be proc hir_node_type from HIR with decl

        Note: Generate class
        If decl_type is equal to HIR.HIR_CLASS:
            proc generate_class with ctx, decl
            proc emit_blank_line from ctx
        End If

        Note: Generate function
        If decl_type is equal to HIR.HIR_FUNCTION:
            proc generate_function with ctx, decl
            proc emit_blank_line from ctx
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: CLASS GENERATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
MATLAB classdef syntax is rigid: members must be partitioned into separate
properties/methods/events blocks, each with its own end. The walker first
buckets members by HIR kind so each block emits contiguously, mirroring
the language requirement. The current_class field is saved/restored across
nested classes (which MATLAB allows in package directories) so the inner
class does not corrupt the outer class context.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_class" takes ctx as Integer, class_node as Integer:
    Note: Save previous class context
    Let prev_class be ctx.current_class
    Set ctx.current_class to class_node

    Note: Build classdef declaration
    Let class_name be proc hir_get_class_name from HIR with class_node
    Let class_line be proc string_concat from StringCore with "classdef ", class_name

    Note: Add base class if present (< BaseClass syntax)
    Let base_class be proc hir_get_base_class from HIR with class_node
    If base_class is not equal to 0:
        Let base_type be proc generate_type with ctx, base_class
        Set class_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with class_line, " < "
        Set class_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with class_line, base_type
    End If

    proc emit_line with ctx, class_line
    proc increase_indent from ctx

    Note: Check for properties, methods, events, enumeration
    Let members be proc hir_get_class_members from HIR with class_node

    Note: Separate members by type
    Let properties be proc list_create from ListCore
    Let methods be proc list_create from ListCore
    Let i be 0
    Let member_count be proc list_length from ListCore with members

    While i is less than member_count:
        Let member be proc list_get from ListCore with members, i
        Let member_type be proc hir_node_type from HIR with member

        If member_type is equal to HIR.HIR_FIELD:
            proc list_append from ListCore with properties, member
        End If

        If member_type is equal to HIR.HIR_METHOD:
            proc list_append from ListCore with methods, member
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Generate properties block
    Let prop_count be proc list_length from ListCore with properties
    If prop_count is greater than 0:
        proc emit_blank_line from ctx
        proc emit_line with ctx, "properties"
        proc increase_indent from ctx

        Set i to 0
        While i is less than prop_count:
            Let property be proc list_get from ListCore with properties, i
            Let prop_name be proc hir_get_field_name from HIR with property

            Note: Check for initializer
            Let initializer be proc hir_get_field_initializer from HIR with property
            If initializer is not equal to 0:
                Let init_expr be proc generate_expression with ctx, initializer
                Let prop_line be proc string_concat from StringCore with prop_name, " = "
                Set prop_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with prop_line, init_expr
                proc emit_line with ctx, prop_line
            Otherwise:
                proc emit_line with ctx, prop_name
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        proc decrease_indent from ctx
        proc emit_line with ctx, "end"
    End If

    Note: Generate methods block
    Let method_count be proc list_length from ListCore with methods
    If method_count is greater than 0:
        proc emit_blank_line from ctx
        proc emit_line with ctx, "methods"
        proc increase_indent from ctx

        Set i to 0
        While i is less than method_count:
            Let method be proc list_get from ListCore with methods, i
            proc emit_blank_line from ctx
            proc generate_method with ctx, method
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        proc decrease_indent from ctx
        proc emit_line with ctx, "end"
    End If

    Note: Check for MATLAB events metadata
    Let events be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with class_node, "matlab_events"
    If events is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_blank_line from ctx
        proc emit_line with ctx, "events"
        proc increase_indent from ctx

        Let event_count be proc list_length from ListCore with events
        Set i to 0
        While i is less than event_count:
            Let event_name be proc list_get from ListCore with events, i
            proc emit_line with ctx, event_name
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        proc decrease_indent from ctx
        proc emit_line with ctx, "end"
    End If

    Note: Check for enumeration metadata
    Let is_enum be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with class_node, "matlab_enumeration"
    If is_enum is equal to 1:
        proc emit_blank_line from ctx
        proc emit_line with ctx, "enumeration"
        proc increase_indent from ctx

        Note: Enumeration values are in properties
        Set i to 0
        While i is less than prop_count:
            Set property to proc list_get from ListCore with properties, i
            Let enum_val be proc hir_get_field_name from HIR with property
            proc emit_line with ctx, enum_val
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        proc decrease_indent from ctx
        proc emit_line with ctx, "end"
    End If

    proc decrease_indent from ctx
    proc emit_line with ctx, "end"

    Note: Restore previous class context
    Set ctx.current_class to prev_class
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: FUNCTION GENERATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
MATLAB functions support multiple named return values via the
'[a, b] = func(...)' syntax, which is preserved by reading the
"matlab_output_params" metadata bag the frontend stuffed onto the HIR
node. Without that metadata we fall back to single-output emission keyed
on the HIR return type; void returns omit the assignment entirely. The
current_function context is saved/restored so nested anonymous functions
do not lose the enclosing scope.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_function" takes ctx as Integer, func_node as Integer:
    Note: Save previous function context
    Let prev_function be ctx.current_function
    Set ctx.current_function to func_node

    Note: Check for MATLAB multiple output parameters
    Let output_params be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with func_node, "matlab_output_params"
    Let has_multiple_outputs be 0
    If output_params is not equal to 0:
        Set has_multiple_outputs to 1
    End If

    Note: Build function declaration
    Let func_line be "function "

    Note: Add output parameters
    If has_multiple_outputs is equal to 1:
        Note: Multiple outputs: function [out1, out2] = func(...)
        Set func_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with func_line, "["
        Let output_count be proc list_length from ListCore with output_params
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than output_count:
            Let output_name be proc list_get from ListCore with output_params, i
            Set func_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with func_line, output_name
            If i is less than output_count minus 1:
                Set func_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with func_line, ", "
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        Set func_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with func_line, "] = "
    Otherwise:
        Note: Single output or void
        Let return_type be proc hir_get_return_type from HIR with func_node
        If return_type is not equal to HIR.HIR_TYPE_VOID:
            Note: Check for single output name
            Let single_output be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with func_node, "matlab_single_output"
            If single_output is not equal to 0:
                Set func_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with func_line, single_output
                Set func_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with func_line, " = "
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Add function name
    Let func_name be proc hir_get_function_name from HIR with func_node
    Set func_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with func_line, func_name

    Note: Add input parameters
    Let params be proc hir_get_parameters from HIR with func_node
    Let param_count be proc list_length from ListCore with params
    Set func_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with func_line, "("

    If param_count is greater than 0:
        Set i to 0
        While i is less than param_count:
            Let param be proc list_get from ListCore with params, i
            Let param_name be proc hir_get_parameter_name from HIR with param
            Set func_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with func_line, param_name
            If i is less than param_count minus 1:
                Set func_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with func_line, ", "
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Set func_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with func_line, ")"
    proc emit_line with ctx, func_line

    Note: Generate function body
    proc increase_indent from ctx
    Let body be proc hir_get_function_body from HIR with func_node
    If body is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_statement with ctx, body
    End If
    proc decrease_indent from ctx

    proc emit_line with ctx, "end"

    Note: Restore previous function context
    Set ctx.current_function to prev_function
End Process

@Reasoning:
Methods inside MATLAB classdefs share the same 'function' keyword as
free-standing functions but live inside a methods block; the structural
emission is therefore identical to generate_function except this routine
is always invoked under the methods-block indent context established by
generate_class. The first parameter convention in MATLAB methods is the
object handle (typically 'obj') which the HIR already encodes as a normal
parameter, so no special-casing is required here.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_method" takes ctx as Integer, method_node as Integer:
    Note: Methods in MATLAB classes are similar to functions but inside methods block
    Note: Reuse function generation logic

    Note: Save previous function context
    Let prev_function be ctx.current_function
    Set ctx.current_function to method_node

    Note: Check for MATLAB multiple output parameters
    Let output_params be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with method_node, "matlab_output_params"
    Let has_multiple_outputs be 0
    If output_params is not equal to 0:
        Set has_multiple_outputs to 1
    End If

    Note: Build method declaration
    Let method_line be "function "

    Note: Add output parameters
    If has_multiple_outputs is equal to 1:
        Set method_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with method_line, "["
        Let output_count be proc list_length from ListCore with output_params
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than output_count:
            Let output_name be proc list_get from ListCore with output_params, i
            Set method_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with method_line, output_name
            If i is less than output_count minus 1:
                Set method_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with method_line, ", "
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        Set method_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with method_line, "] = "
    Otherwise:
        Let return_type be proc hir_get_return_type from HIR with method_node
        If return_type is not equal to HIR.HIR_TYPE_VOID:
            Let single_output be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with method_node, "matlab_single_output"
            If single_output is not equal to 0:
                Set method_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with method_line, single_output
                Set method_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with method_line, " = "
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Add method name
    Let method_name be proc hir_get_method_name from HIR with method_node
    Set method_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with method_line, method_name

    Note: Add parameters (first parameter is typically 'obj' or 'this')
    Let params be proc hir_get_parameters from HIR with method_node
    Let param_count be proc list_length from ListCore with params
    Set method_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with method_line, "("

    If param_count is greater than 0:
        Set i to 0
        While i is less than param_count:
            Let param be proc list_get from ListCore with params, i
            Let param_name be proc hir_get_parameter_name from HIR with param
            Set method_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with method_line, param_name
            If i is less than param_count minus 1:
                Set method_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with method_line, ", "
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Set method_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with method_line, ")"
    proc emit_line with ctx, method_line

    Note: Generate method body
    proc increase_indent from ctx
    Let body be proc hir_get_method_body from HIR with method_node
    If body is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_statement with ctx, body
    End If
    proc decrease_indent from ctx

    proc emit_line with ctx, "end"

    Note: Restore previous function context
    Set ctx.current_function to prev_function
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: STATEMENT GENERATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
The dispatcher routes each HIR statement kind to its specialised emitter.
Break and continue have no body, so they are emitted inline rather than
delegating, keeping the noise low. Expression statements must always be
terminated with a semicolon in MATLAB to suppress automatic echoing of
the result to the command window, so they receive the trailing ';' here.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_statement" takes ctx as Integer, stmt_node as Integer:
    Let stmt_type be proc hir_node_type from HIR with stmt_node

    Note: Block statement
    If stmt_type is equal to HIR.HIR_BLOCK:
        proc generate_block_statement with ctx, stmt_node
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Let/variable declaration
    If stmt_type is equal to HIR.HIR_LET_STATEMENT:
        proc generate_let_statement with ctx, stmt_node
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Assignment statement
    If stmt_type is equal to HIR.HIR_SET_STATEMENT:
        proc generate_set_statement with ctx, stmt_node
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: If statement
    If stmt_type is equal to HIR.HIR_IF_STATEMENT:
        proc generate_if_statement with ctx, stmt_node
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: While loop
    If stmt_type is equal to HIR.HIR_WHILE_STATEMENT:
        proc generate_while_statement with ctx, stmt_node
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: For loop
    If stmt_type is equal to HIR.HIR_FOR_STATEMENT:
        proc generate_for_statement with ctx, stmt_node
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Match/switch statement
    If stmt_type is equal to HIR.HIR_MATCH_STATEMENT:
        proc generate_match_statement with ctx, stmt_node
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Try statement
    If stmt_type is equal to HIR.HIR_TRY_STATEMENT:
        proc generate_try_statement with ctx, stmt_node
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Return statement
    If stmt_type is equal to HIR.HIR_RETURN_STATEMENT:
        proc generate_return_statement with ctx, stmt_node
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Break statement
    If stmt_type is equal to HIR.HIR_BREAK_STATEMENT:
        proc emit_line with ctx, "break"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Continue statement
    If stmt_type is equal to HIR.HIR_CONTINUE_STATEMENT:
        proc emit_line with ctx, "continue"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Expression statement
    If stmt_type is equal to HIR.HIR_EXPRESSION_STATEMENT:
        Let expr be proc hir_get_expression from HIR with stmt_node
        Let expr_str be proc generate_expression with ctx, expr
        Let stmt_line be proc string_concat from StringCore with expr_str, ";"
        proc emit_line with ctx, stmt_line
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
The matlab_spmd metadata maps HIR blocks onto MATLAB's Parallel Computing
Toolbox 'spmd' construct, which runs the body across workers. The opening
keyword and matching 'end' are inserted only when the metadata is present
so vanilla blocks still flatten into the parent scope with no extra
nesting (MATLAB has no anonymous block syntax).
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_block_statement" takes ctx as Integer, block_node as Integer:
    Note: Check for SPMD metadata
    Let is_spmd be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with block_node, "matlab_spmd"
    If is_spmd is equal to 1:
        proc emit_line with ctx, "spmd"
        proc increase_indent from ctx
    End If

    Let statements be proc hir_get_block_statements from HIR with block_node
    Let stmt_count be proc list_length from ListCore with statements
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than stmt_count:
        Let stmt be proc list_get from ListCore with statements, i
        proc generate_statement with ctx, stmt
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Close SPMD block if needed
    If is_spmd is equal to 1:
        proc decrease_indent from ctx
        proc emit_line with ctx, "end"
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
MATLAB does not require variable declarations - a variable simply springs
into existence on first assignment. Lets without an initializer therefore
emit no MATLAB code; only initialised lets become 'var = expr;' lines.
This matches MATLAB's runtime semantics and avoids producing dead
assignments to placeholder values.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_let_statement" takes ctx as Integer, let_node as Integer:
    Note: MATLAB doesn't require explicit variable declarations
    Note: Generate assignment if there's an initializer
    Let initializer be proc hir_get_let_initializer from HIR with let_node
    If initializer is not equal to 0:
        Let var_name be proc hir_get_let_variable_name from HIR with let_node
        Let init_expr be proc generate_expression with ctx, initializer
        Let let_line be proc string_concat from StringCore with var_name, " = "
        Set let_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with let_line, init_expr
        Set let_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with let_line, ";"
        proc emit_line with ctx, let_line
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Both the target and the value are arbitrary expressions because MATLAB
supports complex lvalues (field access, indexed assignment, parenthesised
deindex). Delegating to generate_expression for both sides lets the same
indexing/member emitters be reused; the trailing ';' suppresses the
implicit echo of the assigned value.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_set_statement" takes ctx as Integer, set_node as Integer:
    Let target be proc hir_get_set_target from HIR with set_node
    Let value be proc hir_get_set_value from HIR with set_node

    Let target_expr be proc generate_expression with ctx, target
    Let value_expr be proc generate_expression with ctx, value

    Let set_line be proc string_concat from StringCore with target_expr, " = "
    Set set_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with set_line, value_expr
    Set set_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with set_line, ";"
    proc emit_line with ctx, set_line
End Process

@Reasoning:
MATLAB's if/else uses 'else' (not 'elseif' for a separate-branch case) and
requires a closing 'end'. The HIR's else-block is itself an If node when
chained, so the recursive call into generate_statement on the else block
naturally produces the cascaded 'else if ... end' shape mirroring HIR
structure without dedicated elseif handling.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_if_statement" takes ctx as Integer, if_node as Integer:
    Let condition be proc hir_get_if_condition from HIR with if_node
    Let then_block be proc hir_get_if_then from HIR with if_node
    Let else_block be proc hir_get_if_else from HIR with if_node

    Note: Generate if condition
    Let cond_expr be proc generate_expression with ctx, condition
    Let if_line be proc string_concat from StringCore with "if ", cond_expr
    proc emit_line with ctx, if_line

    Note: Generate then block
    proc increase_indent from ctx
    proc generate_statement with ctx, then_block
    proc decrease_indent from ctx

    Note: Generate else block if present
    If else_block is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_line with ctx, "else"
        proc increase_indent from ctx
        proc generate_statement with ctx, else_block
        proc decrease_indent from ctx
    End If

    proc emit_line with ctx, "end"
End Process

@Reasoning:
MATLAB's while loop syntax is 'while cond ... end'. There is no
do-while construct, so HIR's HIR_DO_WHILE would have been rewritten by
the lowering pass before reaching this emitter; only HIR_WHILE_STATEMENT
arrives here and it maps one-to-one onto the MATLAB form.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_while_statement" takes ctx as Integer, while_node as Integer:
    Let condition be proc hir_get_while_condition from HIR with while_node
    Let body be proc hir_get_while_body from HIR with while_node

    Let cond_expr be proc generate_expression with ctx, condition
    Let while_line be proc string_concat from StringCore with "while ", cond_expr
    proc emit_line with ctx, while_line

    proc increase_indent from ctx
    proc generate_statement with ctx, body
    proc decrease_indent from ctx

    proc emit_line with ctx, "end"
End Process

@Reasoning:
The matlab_parfor metadata selects between sequential 'for' and Parallel
Computing Toolbox 'parfor', which has identical syntax but different
runtime semantics (independent iterations distributed across workers).
MATLAB's for-each operates on the columns of the iterable, so the HIR
iterable should already be lowered to a row vector or matrix shape by the
frontend before reaching this emitter.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_for_statement" takes ctx as Integer, for_node as Integer:
    Let iterator_var be proc hir_get_for_iterator from HIR with for_node
    Let iterable be proc hir_get_for_iterable from HIR with for_node
    Let body be proc hir_get_for_body from HIR with for_node

    Let var_name be proc hir_get_symbol_name from HIR with iterator_var
    Let iter_expr be proc generate_expression with ctx, iterable

    Note: Check if this is a parallel for (parfor)
    Let is_parfor be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with for_node, "matlab_parfor"

    Let for_line be ""
    If is_parfor is equal to 1:
        Set for_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with "parfor ", var_name
    Otherwise:
        Set for_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with "for ", var_name
    End If

    Set for_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with for_line, " = "
    Set for_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with for_line, iter_expr
    proc emit_line with ctx, for_line

    proc increase_indent from ctx
    proc generate_statement with ctx, body
    proc decrease_indent from ctx

    proc emit_line with ctx, "end"
End Process

@Reasoning:
HIR match is lowered to MATLAB switch, which supports literal cases and a
catch-all 'otherwise' clause but not destructuring or guards. The frontend
must have already simplified guard-bearing patterns into nested if/else
chains before reaching this point; this emitter handles only the simple
switch form.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_match_statement" takes ctx as Integer, match_node as Integer:
    Note: HIR match maps to MATLAB switch
    Let expression be proc hir_get_match_expression from HIR with match_node
    Let arms be proc hir_get_match_arms from HIR with match_node

    Let expr_str be proc generate_expression with ctx, expression
    Let switch_line be proc string_concat from StringCore with "switch ", expr_str
    proc emit_line with ctx, switch_line

    proc increase_indent from ctx

    Note: Generate case clauses
    Let arm_count be proc list_length from ListCore with arms
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than arm_count:
        Let when_clause be proc list_get from ListCore with arms, i
        proc generate_when_clause with ctx, when_clause
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc decrease_indent from ctx
    proc emit_line with ctx, "end"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Wildcard arms are emitted as MATLAB's 'otherwise' which must appear last
in a switch block; the dispatcher in generate_match_statement is
responsible for emitting arms in declaration order so the otherwise lands
at the end. Non-wildcard patterns prefer pre-computed pattern_value
strings for literal arms, falling back to a full expression render for
complex patterns (cell arrays, ranges).
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_when_clause" takes ctx as Integer, when_node as Integer:
    Let pattern be proc hir_get_when_pattern from HIR with when_node
    Let body be proc hir_get_when_body from HIR with when_node

    Note: Check pattern type
    Let pattern_type be proc hir_get_pattern_type from HIR with pattern

    Note: Wildcard pattern = otherwise
    If pattern_type is equal to HIR.HIR_PATTERN_WILDCARD:
        proc emit_line with ctx, "otherwise"
    Otherwise:
        Note: Regular pattern = case
        Note: Generate MATLAB case with pattern value (literal or complex)
        Let case_line be "case "

        Note: Extract pattern value - handles both literals and complex patterns
        Let pattern_value be proc hir_get_pattern_value from HIR with pattern
        If pattern_value is not equal to 0:
            Note: Literal pattern - use direct value
            Set case_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with case_line, pattern_value
        Otherwise:
            Note: Complex pattern (e.g., ranges, guards) - generate full expression
            Let pattern_expr be proc generate_expression from ctx with pattern
            Set case_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with case_line, pattern_expr
        End If

        proc emit_line with ctx, case_line
    End If

    proc increase_indent from ctx
    proc generate_statement with ctx, body
    proc decrease_indent from ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
MATLAB exception handling has only a single catch clause (no
catch-by-type, no finally), so we collapse a multi-clause HIR catch chain
into the first clause and ignore subsequent clauses. The exception
variable, when bound, appears as an identifier following the catch
keyword - MATLAB's 'catch err' form.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_try_statement" takes ctx as Integer, try_node as Integer:
    Let try_block be proc hir_get_try_block from HIR with try_node
    Let catch_clauses be proc hir_get_catch_clauses from HIR with try_node

    proc emit_line with ctx, "try"
    proc increase_indent from ctx
    proc generate_statement with ctx, try_block
    proc decrease_indent from ctx

    Note: Generate catch clause (MATLAB has single catch)
    Let catch_count be proc list_length from ListCore with catch_clauses
    If catch_count is greater than 0:
        Let catch_clause be proc list_get from ListCore with catch_clauses, 0
        Let exception_var be proc hir_get_catch_exception_var from HIR with catch_clause
        Let catch_body be proc hir_get_catch_body from HIR with catch_clause

        Note: MATLAB catch with exception variable
        Let catch_line be "catch"
        If exception_var is not equal to 0:
            Let var_name be proc hir_get_symbol_name from HIR with exception_var
            Set catch_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with catch_line, " "
            Set catch_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with catch_line, var_name
        End If
        proc emit_line with ctx, catch_line

        proc increase_indent from ctx
        proc generate_statement with ctx, catch_body
        proc decrease_indent from ctx
    End If

    proc emit_line with ctx, "end"
End Process

@Reasoning:
MATLAB's 'return' carries no expression - the function's output is
whatever was last assigned to the declared output variables. When the
HIR carries a return expression, we synthesise an assignment to the
first output variable (resolved from the surrounding function's
matlab_output_params metadata) before emitting the bare 'return', which
preserves the source's intended return value through the universal
translation round-trip.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_return_statement" takes ctx as Integer, return_node as Integer:
    Note: MATLAB uses 'return' for early exit, actual return values are via output variables
    Let return_expr be proc hir_get_return_expression from HIR with return_node

    If return_expr is not equal to 0:
        Note: If there's a return expression, assign to output variable first
        Note: Proper handling assigns to output variables based on function metadata
        Let output_vars be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with ctx, "matlab_output_params"
        Let expr_str be proc generate_expression with ctx, return_expr

        If output_vars is not equal to 0 and length of output_vars is greater than 0:
            Note: Assign to first output variable
            Let first_output be output_vars at index 0
            Let return_line be proc string_concat from StringCore with first_output, " = "
            Set return_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with return_line, expr_str
        Otherwise:
            Note: No output variables - use comment to indicate return value
            Set return_line to proc string_concat from StringCore with "% return ", expr_str
        End If
        proc emit_line with ctx, return_line
    End If

    proc emit_line with ctx, "return"
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: EXPRESSION GENERATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
The dispatcher returns a string rather than emitting because expressions
nest arbitrarily - they may be concatenated, embedded in conditions, or
passed as arguments to other expressions. Returning "unknown_expr" rather
than raising an error preserves emission stability for HIR shapes that
the MATLAB backend has not yet been taught about, while still producing
recognisable output for diagnostic inspection.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_expression" takes ctx as Integer, expr_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let expr_type be proc hir_node_type from HIR with expr_node

    Note: Literal expressions
    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_NUMBER_LITERAL:
        Let value be proc hir_get_literal_value from HIR with expr_node
        Return value
    End If

    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_STRING_LITERAL:
        Set value to proc hir_get_literal_value from HIR with expr_node
        Let quoted be proc string_concat from StringCore with "'", value
        Set quoted to proc string_concat from StringCore with quoted, "'"
        Return quoted
    End If

    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_BOOLEAN_LITERAL:
        Set value to proc hir_get_literal_value from HIR with expr_node
        If value is equal to 1:
            Return "true"
        Otherwise:
            Return "false"
        End If
    End If

    Note: Identifier
    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_IDENTIFIER:
        Let id_name be proc hir_get_identifier_name from HIR with expr_node
        Return id_name
    End If

    Note: Array literal (matrix or cell)
    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_ARRAY_LITERAL:
        Return proc generate_array_literal with ctx, expr_node
    End If

    Note: Binary expression
    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_BINARY_EXPR:
        Return proc generate_binary_expression with ctx, expr_node
    End If

    Note: Unary expression
    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_UNARY_EXPR:
        Return proc generate_unary_expression with ctx, expr_node
    End If

    Note: Call expression
    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_CALL_EXPR:
        Return proc generate_call_expression with ctx, expr_node
    End If

    Note: Index expression
    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_INDEX_EXPR:
        Return proc generate_index_expression with ctx, expr_node
    End If

    Note: Member expression
    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_MEMBER_EXPR:
        Return proc generate_member_expression with ctx, expr_node
    End If

    Note: Function pointer (function handle)
    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_FUNCTION_POINTER:
        Return proc generate_function_pointer with ctx, expr_node
    End If

    Note: Lambda expression (anonymous function)
    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_LAMBDA_EXPR:
        Return proc generate_lambda_expression with ctx, expr_node
    End If

    Note: Range expression (colon operator)
    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_RANGE_EXPR:
        Return proc generate_range_expression with ctx, expr_node
    End If

    Return "unknown_expr"
End Process

@Reasoning:
MATLAB has two distinct array literal forms: square brackets produce
matrices/vectors with comma-or-space separated elements, while curly
braces produce cell arrays for heterogeneous storage. The matlab_cell
metadata selects between them; cell elements are comma-separated while
matrix elements use spaces (mimicking MATLAB's standard formatting).
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_array_literal" takes ctx as Integer, array_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let elements be proc hir_get_array_elements from HIR with array_node
    Let elem_count be proc list_length from ListCore with elements

    Note: Check if this is a MATLAB matrix or cell array
    Let is_cell be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with array_node, "matlab_cell"
    Let is_matrix be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with array_node, "matlab_matrix"

    Let result be ""

    If is_cell is equal to 1:
        Note: Cell array: {elem1, elem2, ...}
        Set result to "{"
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than elem_count:
            Let elem be proc list_get from ListCore with elements, i
            Let elem_expr be proc generate_expression with ctx, elem
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, elem_expr
            If i is less than elem_count minus 1:
                Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, ", "
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, "}"
    Otherwise:
        Note: Regular array/matrix: [elem1 elem2 ...]
        Set result to "["
        Set i to 0
        While i is less than elem_count:
            Set elem to proc list_get from ListCore with elements, i
            Set elem_expr to proc generate_expression with ctx, elem
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, elem_expr
            If i is less than elem_count minus 1:
                Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, " "
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, "]"
    End If

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
MATLAB distinguishes matrix and element-wise operators using a leading
dot prefix (.* vs *, ./ vs /, .^ vs ^). The matlab_elementwise metadata
selects the dot-prefixed form, which is essential for preserving the
intended semantics across the round-trip: element-wise multiplication of
two same-shape matrices is fundamentally different from matrix product.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_binary_expression" takes ctx as Integer, binary_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let operator be proc hir_get_binary_operator from HIR with binary_node
    Let left be proc hir_get_binary_left from HIR with binary_node
    Let right be proc hir_get_binary_right from HIR with binary_node

    Let left_expr be proc generate_expression with ctx, left
    Let right_expr be proc generate_expression with ctx, right

    Note: Check if element-wise operation
    Let is_elementwise be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with binary_node, "matlab_elementwise"

    Note: Map HIR operator to MATLAB operator
    Let op_str be proc map_hir_operator_to_matlab with operator, is_elementwise

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringCore with left_expr, " "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, op_str
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, " "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, right_expr

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
The mapping table embodies the v0.0.8.5 contract between HIR operator
codes and MATLAB syntax: arithmetic ops branch on is_elementwise for
matrix-vs-array semantics, relational ops are direct (with ~= for
inequality rather than !=), and logical ops use the short-circuit
&&/|| forms (which require scalar operands in MATLAB) versus the
element-wise &/| forms. The default of "+" mirrors MATLAB's behaviour
of treating unknown binary contexts as numeric addition rather than
raising a compile error.
@End Reasoning
Process called "map_hir_operator_to_matlab" takes operator as Integer, is_elementwise as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Map HIR operators to MATLAB operators

    Note: Arithmetic operators
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_ADD:
        Return "+"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_SUBTRACT:
        Return "-"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_MULTIPLY:
        If is_elementwise is equal to 1:
            Return ".*"
        Otherwise:
            Return "*"
        End If
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_DIVIDE:
        If is_elementwise is equal to 1:
            Return "./"
        Otherwise:
            Return "/"
        End If
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_POWER:
        If is_elementwise is equal to 1:
            Return ".^"
        Otherwise:
            Return "^"
        End If
    End If

    Note: Relational operators
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_EQUAL:
        Return "=="
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_NOT_EQUAL:
        Return "~="
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_LESS_THAN:
        Return "<"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_LESS_EQUAL:
        Return "<="
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_GREATER_THAN:
        Return ">"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_GREATER_EQUAL:
        Return ">="
    End If

    Note: Logical operators
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_LOGICAL_AND:
        Return "&&"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_LOGICAL_OR:
        Return "||"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_BITWISE_AND:
        Return "&"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_BITWISE_OR:
        Return "|"
    End If

    Return "+"
End Process

@Reasoning:
The transpose operator is the most subtle unary case: MATLAB uses ' for
complex-conjugate transpose and .' for the plain transpose, which differ
only when the operand has complex entries. The matlab_complex_conjugate
metadata records which variant the source intended so we never silently
swap a real-only transpose for the conjugate form, which would change
results when the value type later became complex.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_unary_expression" takes ctx as Integer, unary_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let operator be proc hir_get_unary_operator from HIR with unary_node
    Let operand be proc hir_get_unary_operand from HIR with unary_node

    Let operand_expr be proc generate_expression with ctx, operand

    Note: Check for transpose operator
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_TRANSPOSE:
        Let is_complex be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with unary_node, "matlab_complex_conjugate"
        If is_complex is equal to 1:
            Let result be proc string_concat from StringCore with operand_expr, "'"
            Return result
        Otherwise:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with operand_expr, ".'"
            Return result
        End If
    End If

    Note: Other unary operators
    Let op_str be "-"
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_LOGICAL_NOT:
        Set op_str to "~"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_PLUS:
        Set op_str to "+"
    End If

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with op_str, operand_expr
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
MATLAB call syntax uses parentheses for both function calls and array
indexing - the distinction is resolved by the callee being a function
handle or identifier vs. a variable. Since the HIR carries the
distinction explicitly via the HIR_CALL vs HIR_INDEX nodes, the emitter
only sees calls here and can use parentheses unambiguously.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_call_expression" takes ctx as Integer, call_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let callee be proc hir_get_call_callee from HIR with call_node
    Let arguments be proc hir_get_call_arguments from HIR with call_node

    Let callee_expr be proc generate_expression with ctx, callee

    Note: Generate arguments
    Let arg_count be proc list_length from ListCore with arguments
    Let args_str be ""
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than arg_count:
        Let arg be proc list_get from ListCore with arguments, i
        Let arg_expr be proc generate_expression with ctx, arg
        Set args_str to proc string_concat from StringCore with args_str, arg_expr
        If i is less than arg_count minus 1:
            Set args_str to proc string_concat from StringCore with args_str, ", "
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringCore with callee_expr, "("
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, args_str
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, ")"

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
MATLAB indexing has three forms: parentheses (arrays/matrices), braces
(cell unwrap), and dynamic field syntax obj.(expr) for runtime-computed
field names on structs. The metadata flags resolve which form to emit;
without them we default to parentheses since that is the most common
indexing operation across MATLAB code.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_index_expression" takes ctx as Integer, index_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let object be proc hir_get_index_object from HIR with index_node
    Let index be proc hir_get_index_index from HIR with index_node

    Let object_expr be proc generate_expression with ctx, object
    Let index_expr be proc generate_expression with ctx, index

    Note: Check for MATLAB dynamic field access
    Let is_dynamic_field be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with index_node, "matlab_dynamic_field"
    If is_dynamic_field is equal to 1:
        Note: Generate obj.(field_expr) syntax
        Let result be proc string_concat from StringCore with object_expr, ".("
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, index_expr
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, ")"
        Return result
    End If

    Note: Check if cell indexing {braces} vs array indexing (parens)
    Let is_cell be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with index_node, "matlab_cell_indexing"

    Set result to object_expr
    If is_cell is equal to 1:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, "{"
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, index_expr
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, "}"
    Otherwise:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, "("
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, index_expr
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, ")"
    End If

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Static dot-access lives in this dedicated emitter; the dynamic form is
handled by generate_index_expression with the matlab_dynamic_field flag.
The member name is taken verbatim from the HIR rather than resolved
through any symbol table because MATLAB resolves struct fields at runtime
- the emitter must not alter the spelling.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_member_expression" takes ctx as Integer, member_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let object be proc hir_get_member_object from HIR with member_node
    Let member_name be proc hir_get_member_name from HIR with member_node

    Let object_expr be proc generate_expression with ctx, object

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringCore with object_expr, "."
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, member_name

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
MATLAB function handles use the '@' prefix syntax. This emitter assumes
the function name is a simple identifier; package-qualified handles
(e.g. @mypackage.myfunc) flow through the same path because the HIR
already encodes the dotted name as the function pointer name.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_function_pointer" takes ctx as Integer, func_ptr_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: MATLAB function handle: @functionName
    Let func_name be proc hir_get_function_pointer_name from HIR with func_ptr_node

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringCore with "@", func_name
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
MATLAB anonymous functions use '@(params) expr' and are restricted to a
single expression body; the HIR lowering pass must have already inlined
multi-statement lambdas into helper functions before reaching this
emitter. Parameter names are emitted verbatim from the HIR because
MATLAB does not require declared types.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_lambda_expression" takes ctx as Integer, lambda_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: MATLAB anonymous function: @(params) expression
    Let parameters be proc hir_get_lambda_parameters from HIR with lambda_node
    Let body be proc hir_get_lambda_body from HIR with lambda_node

    Let result be "@("

    Note: Generate parameter list
    Let param_count be proc list_length from ListCore with parameters
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than param_count:
        Let param be proc list_get from ListCore with parameters, i
        Let param_name be proc hir_get_parameter_name from HIR with param
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, param_name
        If i is less than param_count minus 1:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, ", "
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, ") "

    Note: Generate body expression
    Let body_expr be proc generate_expression with ctx, body
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, body_expr

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
The colon operator is overloaded in MATLAB: a bare ':' selects every
element of an indexing dimension, 'a:b' creates a 1-step vector from a
to b, and 'a:s:b' uses step s. The matlab_colon_all metadata recognises
the bare-colon form so the emitter does not need a placeholder start/end
pair. When step is null we omit it rather than emit '1:' which would
add a redundant step.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_range_expression" takes ctx as Integer, range_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: MATLAB colon operator: start:end or start:step:end
    Let start be proc hir_get_range_start from HIR with range_node
    Let end_val be proc hir_get_range_end from HIR with range_node
    Let step be proc hir_get_range_step from HIR with range_node

    Note: Check for special ":" (all elements)
    Let is_colon_all be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with range_node, "matlab_colon_all"
    If is_colon_all is equal to 1:
        Return ":"
    End If

    Let start_expr be proc generate_expression with ctx, start
    Let end_expr be proc generate_expression with ctx, end_val

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringCore with start_expr, ":"

    Note: Add step if present
    If step is not equal to 0:
        Let step_expr be proc generate_expression with ctx, step
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, step_expr
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, ":"
    End If

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, end_expr

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returning "any" when the type id has no mapping reflects MATLAB's
duck-typed reality - any unknown HIR type can hold any MATLAB value at
runtime. The type string surfaces only in documentation comments and
classdef inheritance clauses, so the fallback never causes runtime
problems even when it loses precision relative to the HIR type.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_type" takes ctx as Integer, type_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: MATLAB is dynamically typed, so types are mostly for comments
    Let type_id be proc hir_get_type_id from HIR with type_node
    Let type_str be proc dict_get from DictCore with ctx.type_map, proc int_to_string from StringCore with type_id

    If type_str is equal to 0:
        Return "any"
    End If

    Return type_str
End Process
